 most recent outputs of trauma studies. They are written by a selection of leading scholars, associated to some degree with the Hungaro-South African Study Group. Here, trauma is employed as a useful hermeneutical lens, not only for interpreting biblical texts and the contexts in which they were originally produced and functioned but also for providing a useful frame of reference. As a consequence, these various research outputs, each in their own way, confirm that an historical and theological appreciation of these early accounts and interpretations of collective trauma and its implications, (perceived or otherwise), is critical for understanding the essential substance of Jewish cultural identity. As such, these essays are ideal for scholars in the fields of Biblical Studies—particularly those interested in the Pseudepigrapha, the Deuterocanonical books and Cognate literature.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 4aApokryphen. 4aDeuterokanonische Literatur. 4aPseudepigraphen. 7aRELIGION / Ancient.2bisacsh  aApocrypha.  aCognate Literature.  aDeuterocanonical Literature.  aPseudepigrapha.1 aAllen, Nicholas P. L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBalla, Ibolya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeek, Aaron L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoedens, Jaap J. T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoedens, Jacob J. T. , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEfthimiadis-Keith, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGericke, Jaco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHobyane, Risimati S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJordaan, Pier